cmmcno00x003b3v022ahdijek	cmm58y7lt002j3t2wepydt1xl	Which of the following actions constitutes a First-Degree Misdemeanor?	{"Conducting real estate services without a license.","Selling a rental list that contains inaccurate or out-of-date information.","False advertising.","Failing to deposit escrow funds immediately."}	1	{"correct": "Failing to provide accurate and current rental information for a fee is the only First-Degree Misdemeanor specifically listed in real estate law. (Penalty: up to 1 year in jail / $1,000 fine).", "incorrect": ["Unlicensed activity is a Third-Degree Felony.", "", "Most other violations of Chapter 475 (like false advertising or escrow errors) are Second-Degree Misdemeanors.", "Most other violations of Chapter 475 (like false advertising or escrow errors) are Second-Degree Misdemeanors."]}	16	chapter	2026-03-04 23:16:06.561	2026-03-04 23:39:29.02	\N	\N	\N	\N	/audio/1772667565428-Failing_to_provide_a.mp3	/timestamps/1772667565428-Failing_to_provide_a.timestamps.json	["/audio/1772667566335-Unlicensed_activity_.mp3", "", "/audio/1772667567660-Most_other_violation.mp3", "/audio/1772667568871-Most_other_violation.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1772667566335-Unlicensed_activity_.timestamps.json", "", "/timestamps/1772667567660-Most_other_violation.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667568871-Most_other_violation.timestamps.json"]	["/audio/1772667561574-Conducting_real_esta.mp3", "/audio/1772667562395-Selling_a_rental_lis.mp3", "/audio/1772667562953-False_advertising_.mp3", "/audio/1772667563633-Failing_to_deposit_e.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1772667561574-Conducting_real_esta.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667562395-Selling_a_rental_lis.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667562953-False_advertising_.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667563633-Failing_to_deposit_e.timestamps.json"]	/audio/1772667560812-Which_of_the_followi.mp3	/timestamps/1772667560812-Which_of_the_followi.timestamps.json
cmmqx6wen003w4be7d0xg91b7	cmmqbpz7v00044be7x0za79d7	If a tenant fails to pay rent on time, the landlord may post a notice giving the tenant how much time to pay or move out?	{"24 hours","3 business days","7 calendar days","30 days"}	1	{"correct": "The landlord must deliver a 3-Day Notice to Pay or Quit. This excludes weekends and legal holidays.", "incorrect": ["Too short.", "", "7 days is for lease violations, not rent.", "Too long."]}	26	chapter	2026-03-14 22:51:31.343	2026-03-14 23:15:18.25	\N	\N	\N	\N	/audio/1773530115635-The_landlord_must_de.mp3	/timestamps/1773530115635-The_landlord_must_de.timestamps.json	["/audio/1773530116401-Too_short_.mp3", "", "/audio/1773530117429-7_days_is_for_lease_.mp3", "/audio/1773530118019-Too_long_.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1773530116401-Too_short_.timestamps.json", "", "/timestamps/1773530117429-7_days_is_for_lease_.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530118019-Too_long_.timestamps.json"]	["/audio/1773530112057-24_hours.mp3", "/audio/1773530112652-3_business_days.mp3", "/audio/1773530113298-7_calendar_days.mp3", "/audio/1773530114004-30_days.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1773530112057-24_hours.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530112652-3_business_days.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530113298-7_calendar_days.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530114004-30_days.timestamps.json"]	/audio/1773530111448-If_a_tenant_fails_to.mp3	/timestamps/1773530111448-If_a_tenant_fails_to.timestamps.json
cmmcnpp6d003d3v02owyu0l0w	cmm58y7lt002j3t2wepydt1xl	A licensee who is found guilty of false advertising (a violation of Chapter 475) has committed which type of crime?	{"First-Degree Misdemeanor","Second-Degree Misdemeanor","Third-Degree Felony","Administrative violation only (not a crime)"}	1	{"correct": "Violation of Chapter 475 is generally a Second-Degree Misdemeanor unless specifically stated otherwise (like rental lists or unlicensed activity). (Penalty: up to 60 days in jail / $500 fine).", "incorrect": ["Reserved for rental list violations.", "", "Reserved for serious offenses like unlicensed activity or exam theft.", "While it is an administrative violation, it is also a criminal misdemeanor."]}	17	chapter	2026-03-04 23:17:25.813	2026-03-04 23:39:37.629	\N	\N	\N	\N	/audio/1772667574949-Violation_of_Chapter.mp3	/timestamps/1772667574949-Violation_of_Chapter.timestamps.json	["/audio/1772667575684-Reserved_for_rental_.mp3", "", "/audio/1772667576604-Reserved_for_serious.mp3", "/audio/1772667577478-While_it_is_an_admin.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1772667575684-Reserved_for_rental_.timestamps.json", "", "/timestamps/1772667576604-Reserved_for_serious.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667577478-While_it_is_an_admin.timestamps.json"]	["/audio/1772667571167-First_Degree_Misdeme.mp3", "/audio/1772667571805-Second_Degree_Misdem.mp3", "/audio/1772667572313-Third_Degree_Felony.mp3", "/audio/1772667573058-Administrative_viola.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1772667571167-First_Degree_Misdeme.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667571805-Second_Degree_Misdem.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667572313-Third_Degree_Felony.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667573058-Administrative_viola.timestamps.json"]	/audio/1772667570432-A_licensee_who_is_fo.mp3	/timestamps/1772667570432-A_licensee_who_is_fo.timestamps.json
cmmcnsv6f003f3v02ivpvo7wd	cmm58y7lt002j3t2wepydt1xl	Which of the following offenses is classified as a Third-Degree Felony?	{"A sales associate collecting a commission directly from a seller","Failing to reconcile an escrow account","Performing real estate services without a valid current license","Failing to maintain a proper office sign"}	2	{"correct": "Unlicensed activity (practicing without a license) is a Third-Degree Felony, the most serious category of crime in real estate law. (Penalty: up to 5 years in prison / $5,000 fine). Other third-degree felonies include falsifying an application and stealing/reproducing the state exam.", "incorrect": ["This is a Second-Degree Misdemeanor.", "This is a Second-Degree Misdemeanor.", "", "This is a Second-Degree Misdemeanor."]}	18	chapter	2026-03-04 23:19:53.559	2026-03-04 23:39:46.21	\N	\N	\N	\N	/audio/1772667583808-Unlicensed_activity_.mp3	/timestamps/1772667583808-Unlicensed_activity_.timestamps.json	["/audio/1772667584638-This_is_a_Second_Deg.mp3", "/audio/1772667585268-This_is_a_Second_Deg.mp3", "", "/audio/1772667585977-This_is_a_Second_Deg.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1772667584638-This_is_a_Second_Deg.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667585268-This_is_a_Second_Deg.timestamps.json", "", "/timestamps/1772667585977-This_is_a_Second_Deg.timestamps.json"]	["/audio/1772667579313-A_sales_associate_co.mp3", "/audio/1772667579989-Failing_to_reconcile.mp3", "/audio/1772667580784-Performing_real_esta.mp3", "/audio/1772667581492-Failing_to_maintain_.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1772667579313-A_sales_associate_co.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667579989-Failing_to_reconcile.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667580784-Performing_real_esta.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667581492-Failing_to_maintain_.timestamps.json"]	/audio/1772667578548-Which_of_the_followi.mp3	/timestamps/1772667578548-Which_of_the_followi.timestamps.json
cmmqx9p87003y4be710a2mxrw	cmmqbpz7v00044be7x0za79d7	A tenant is keeping a dog in a "no pets" apartment (a curable violation). The landlord should issue which type of notice?	{"3-Day Notice to Pay or Quit","7-Day Notice to Cure","7-Day Notice to Vacate","Writ of Possession"}	1	{"correct": "For a lease violation that can be fixed (curable), the landlord gives a 7-Day Notice to Cure. This gives the tenant 7 days to get rid of the dog.", "incorrect": ["Used for non-payment of rent.", "", "Used for non-curable/repeat violations.", "Issued by the court after the eviction lawsuit is won."]}	27	chapter	2026-03-14 22:53:42.006	2026-03-14 23:15:28.111	\N	\N	\N	\N	/audio/1773530125220-For_a_lease_violatio.mp3	/timestamps/1773530125220-For_a_lease_violatio.timestamps.json	["/audio/1773530126063-Used_for_non_payment.mp3", "", "/audio/1773530126890-Used_for_non_curable.mp3", "/audio/1773530127884-Issued_by_the_court_.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1773530126063-Used_for_non_payment.timestamps.json", "", "/timestamps/1773530126890-Used_for_non_curable.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530127884-Issued_by_the_court_.timestamps.json"]	["/audio/1773530120910-3_Day_Notice_to_Pay_.mp3", "/audio/1773530121837-7_Day_Notice_to_Cure.mp3", "/audio/1773530122599-7_Day_Notice_to_Vaca.mp3", "/audio/1773530123219-Writ_of_Possession.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1773530120910-3_Day_Notice_to_Pay_.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530121837-7_Day_Notice_to_Cure.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530122599-7_Day_Notice_to_Vaca.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530123219-Writ_of_Possession.timestamps.json"]	/audio/1773530120012-A_tenant_is_keeping_.mp3	/timestamps/1773530120012-A_tenant_is_keeping_.timestamps.json
cmmqxcfb100404be7yfpq0aka	cmmqbpz7v00044be7x0za79d7	A tenant is caught intentionally destroying the kitchen cabinets (a non-curable violation). The landlord should issue a:	{"3-Day Notice to Pay or Quit","7-Day Notice to Cure","7-Day Notice to Vacate","15-Day Notice of Claim"}	2	{"correct": "For serious destruction or non-curable offenses, the landlord issues a 7-Day Notice to Vacate. The tenant has no option to \\"fix\\" it; they must leave.", "incorrect": ["3-Day Notice to Pay or Quit is used for rent issues.", "7-Day Notice to Cure is used when the problem can be fixed (like noise or unauthorized parking).", "", "15-Day Notice of Claim is related to security deposits, not eviction."]}	28	chapter	2026-03-14 22:55:49.116	2026-03-14 23:15:38.771	\N	\N	\N	\N	/audio/1773530134841-For_serious_destruct.mp3	/timestamps/1773530134841-For_serious_destruct.timestamps.json	["/audio/1773530135903-3_Day_Notice_to_Pay_.mp3", "/audio/1773530137339-7_Day_Notice_to_Cure.mp3", "", "/audio/1773530138617-15_Day_Notice_of_Cla.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1773530135903-3_Day_Notice_to_Pay_.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530137339-7_Day_Notice_to_Cure.timestamps.json", "", "/timestamps/1773530138617-15_Day_Notice_of_Cla.timestamps.json"]	["/audio/1773530130395-3_Day_Notice_to_Pay_.mp3", "/audio/1773530131146-7_Day_Notice_to_Cure.mp3", "/audio/1773530132054-7_Day_Notice_to_Vaca.mp3", "/audio/1773530132948-15_Day_Notice_of_Cla.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1773530130395-3_Day_Notice_to_Pay_.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530131146-7_Day_Notice_to_Cure.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530132054-7_Day_Notice_to_Vaca.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530132948-15_Day_Notice_of_Cla.timestamps.json"]	/audio/1773530129481-A_tenant_is_caught_i.mp3	/timestamps/1773530129481-A_tenant_is_caught_i.timestamps.json
cmmcnvk70003j3v0230ryk5rf	cmm58y7lt002j3t2wepydt1xl	During the disciplinary process against a real estate licensee, who is responsible for preparing and submitting a "Recommended Order" that includes findings of fact and conclusions of law?	{"The Probable Cause Panel","The DBPR Secretary","An Administrative Law Judge","The Florida Real Estate Commission (FREC)"}	2	{"correct": "If a disciplinary case goes to a formal hearing, it is heard by an Administrative Law Judge (ALJ) from the Division of Administrative Hearings (DOAH). After the hearing, the ALJ prepares and submits a \\"Recommended Order\\" outlining the findings of fact, conclusions of law, and a recommended penalty.", "incorrect": ["The Probable Cause Panel acts like a grand jury; they determine if there is enough evidence to file a formal complaint in the first place, but they do not conduct formal hearings or issue recommended orders.", "The Secretary of the Department of Business and Professional Regulation (DBPR) oversees the agency but does not preside over individual licensee hearings or issue recommended orders.", "", "The FREC does not issue the Recommended Order. Instead, the FREC receives the ALJ's recommended order and then issues the Final Order, which is the final decision detailing the actual penalty imposed."]}	19	chapter	2026-03-04 23:21:59.292	2026-03-04 23:39:57.78	\N	\N	\N	\N	/audio/1772667592573-If_a_disciplinary_ca.mp3	/timestamps/1772667592573-If_a_disciplinary_ca.timestamps.json	["/audio/1772667594051-The_Probable_Cause_P.mp3", "/audio/1772667595600-The_Secretary_of_the.mp3", "", "/audio/1772667597591-The_FREC_does_not_is.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1772667594051-The_Probable_Cause_P.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667595600-The_Secretary_of_the.timestamps.json", "", "/timestamps/1772667597591-The_FREC_does_not_is.timestamps.json"]	["/audio/1772667588275-The_Probable_Cause_P.mp3", "/audio/1772667588907-The_DBPR_Secretary.mp3", "/audio/1772667589585-An_Administrative_La.mp3", "/audio/1772667590323-The_Florida_Real_Est.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1772667588275-The_Probable_Cause_P.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667588907-The_DBPR_Secretary.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667589585-An_Administrative_La.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667590323-The_Florida_Real_Est.timestamps.json"]	/audio/1772667587715-During_the_disciplin.mp3	/timestamps/1772667587715-During_the_disciplin.timestamps.json
cmmcnvd4z003h3v02mv098j63	cmm58y7lt002j3t2wepydt1xl	During the disciplinary process against a real estate licensee, who is responsible for preparing and submitting a "Recommended Order" that includes findings of fact and conclusions of law?	{"The Probable Cause Panel","The DBPR Secretary","An Administrative Law Judge","The Florida Real Estate Commission (FREC)"}	2	{"correct": "If a disciplinary case goes to a formal hearing, it is heard by an Administrative Law Judge (ALJ) from the Division of Administrative Hearings (DOAH). After the hearing, the ALJ prepares and submits a \\"Recommended Order\\" outlining the findings of fact, conclusions of law, and a recommended penalty.", "incorrect": ["The Probable Cause Panel acts like a grand jury; they determine if there is enough evidence to file a formal complaint in the first place, but they do not conduct formal hearings or issue recommended orders.", "The Secretary of the Department of Business and Professional Regulation (DBPR) oversees the agency but does not preside over individual licensee hearings or issue recommended orders.", "", "The FREC does not issue the Recommended Order. Instead, the FREC receives the ALJ's recommended order and then issues the Final Order, which is the final decision detailing the actual penalty imposed."]}	19	chapter	2026-03-04 23:21:50.147	2026-03-04 23:40:09.377	\N	\N	\N	\N	/audio/1772667604507-If_a_disciplinary_ca.mp3	/timestamps/1772667604507-If_a_disciplinary_ca.timestamps.json	["/audio/1772667606157-The_Probable_Cause_P.mp3", "/audio/1772667607700-The_Secretary_of_the.mp3", "", "/audio/1772667609226-The_FREC_does_not_is.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1772667606157-The_Probable_Cause_P.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667607700-The_Secretary_of_the.timestamps.json", "", "/timestamps/1772667609226-The_FREC_does_not_is.timestamps.json"]	["/audio/1772667599867-The_Probable_Cause_P.mp3", "/audio/1772667600457-The_DBPR_Secretary.mp3", "/audio/1772667601065-An_Administrative_La.mp3", "/audio/1772667601819-The_Florida_Real_Est.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1772667599867-The_Probable_Cause_P.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667600457-The_DBPR_Secretary.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667601065-An_Administrative_La.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667601819-The_Florida_Real_Est.timestamps.json"]	/audio/1772667599298-During_the_disciplin.mp3	/timestamps/1772667599298-During_the_disciplin.timestamps.json
cmmqxei5h00424be78q0i62kz	cmmqbpz7v00044be7x0za79d7	When a landlord demands advanced rent or a security deposit in Florida, the money:	{"May be deposited in the landlord's account if that account has insurance","Must be kept in a separate account","Must always be held in an interest-bearing account","May be placed in a broker's personal account if a sufficient surety bond has been posted"}	1	{"correct": "Under the Florida Residential Landlord and Tenant Act, a landlord must hold advance rents and security deposits in a separate Florida bank account (meaning it cannot be commingled with their own personal or operating funds).", "incorrect": ["General bank account insurance (like FDIC) does not give a landlord the right to commingle a tenant's deposit with their own money.", "", "The law gives the landlord the choice: the separate account can be either non-interest-bearing or interest-bearing. It is not required to bear interest.", "While a private landlord does have a specific legal option to post a surety bond and mix funds, a licensed real estate broker acting as a property manager is strictly bound by FREC rules. A broker is never permitted to place client escrow funds into their personal account, regardless of whether a bond is posted."]}	29	chapter	2026-03-14 22:57:26.117	2026-03-14 23:15:52.997	\N	\N	\N	\N	/audio/1773530146378-Under_the_Florida_Re.mp3	/timestamps/1773530146378-Under_the_Florida_Re.timestamps.json	["/audio/1773530148184-General_bank_account.mp3", "", "/audio/1773530150035-The_law_gives_the_la.mp3", "/audio/1773530152771-While_a_private_land.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1773530148184-General_bank_account.timestamps.json", "", "/timestamps/1773530150035-The_law_gives_the_la.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530152771-While_a_private_land.timestamps.json"]	["/audio/1773530141126-May_be_deposited_in_.mp3", "/audio/1773530141897-Must_be_kept_in_a_se.mp3", "/audio/1773530142849-Must_always_be_held_.mp3", "/audio/1773530143896-May_be_placed_in_a_b.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1773530141126-May_be_deposited_in_.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530141897-Must_be_kept_in_a_se.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530142849-Must_always_be_held_.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530143896-May_be_placed_in_a_b.timestamps.json"]	/audio/1773530140223-When_a_landlord_dema.mp3	/timestamps/1773530140223-When_a_landlord_dema.timestamps.json
cmmqxhqug00444be7wadvjspx	cmmqbpz7v00044be7x0za79d7	When renting out a single-family home or a duplex in Florida, what is the landlord's statutory obligation regarding smoke detectors?	{"The landlord must install and perpetually maintain the batteries in all smoke detectors throughout the entire duration of the lease.","The tenant is solely responsible for purchasing and installing their own smoke detectors upon moving in.","The landlord is required to install working smoke detectors before the beginning of the lease period, unless agreed to otherwise in writing.","Smoke detectors are only legally required by the state in multi-family apartment buildings with four or more units."}	2	{"correct": "Under Florida Statute 83.51, the landlord of a single-family home or duplex is legally required to install working smoke detection devices before the tenant moves in, unless the landlord and tenant have specifically agreed otherwise in writing.", "incorrect": ["While the landlord must install working smoke detectors prior to occupancy, the law explicitly states they are not obligated to maintain them (like changing out dead batteries) after the tenant has taken possession of the property.", "The initial provision and installation of the equipment is the legal responsibility of the landlord, not the incoming tenant.", "", "Florida law specifically mandates this requirement for single-family homes and duplexes, not just larger multi-family apartment complexes."]}	30	chapter	2026-03-14 22:59:57.352	2026-03-14 23:16:08.18	\N	\N	\N	\N	/audio/1773530163067-Under_Florida_Statut.mp3	/timestamps/1773530163067-Under_Florida_Statut.timestamps.json	["/audio/1773530164780-While_the_landlord_m.mp3", "/audio/1773530166469-The_initial_provisio.mp3", "", "/audio/1773530168025-Florida_law_specific.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1773530164780-While_the_landlord_m.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530166469-The_initial_provisio.timestamps.json", "", "/timestamps/1773530168025-Florida_law_specific.timesta