cmmcnvkaw003l3v0256wt8doj	cmm58y7lt002j3t2wepydt1xl	During the disciplinary process against a real estate licensee, who is responsible for preparing and submitting a "Recommended Order" that includes findings of fact and conclusions of law?	{"The Probable Cause Panel","The DBPR Secretary","An Administrative Law Judge","The Florida Real Estate Commission (FREC)"}	2	{"correct": "If a disciplinary case goes to a formal hearing, it is heard by an Administrative Law Judge (ALJ) from the Division of Administrative Hearings (DOAH). After the hearing, the ALJ prepares and submits a \\"Recommended Order\\" outlining the findings of fact, conclusions of law, and a recommended penalty.", "incorrect": ["The Probable Cause Panel acts like a grand jury; they determine if there is enough evidence to file a formal complaint in the first place, but they do not conduct formal hearings or issue recommended orders.", "The Secretary of the Department of Business and Professional Regulation (DBPR) oversees the agency but does not preside over individual licensee hearings or issue recommended orders.", "", "The FREC does not issue the Recommended Order. Instead, the FREC receives the ALJ's recommended order and then issues the Final Order, which is the final decision detailing the actual penalty imposed."]}	19	chapter	2026-03-04 23:21:59.432	2026-03-04 23:40:20.922	\N	\N	\N	\N	/audio/1772667615935-If_a_disciplinary_ca.mp3	/timestamps/1772667615935-If_a_disciplinary_ca.timestamps.json	["/audio/1772667617553-The_Probable_Cause_P.mp3", "/audio/1772667618962-The_Secretary_of_the.mp3", "", "/audio/1772667620677-The_FREC_does_not_is.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1772667617553-The_Probable_Cause_P.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667618962-The_Secretary_of_the.timestamps.json", "", "/timestamps/1772667620677-The_FREC_does_not_is.timestamps.json"]	["/audio/1772667611821-The_Probable_Cause_P.mp3", "/audio/1772667612444-The_DBPR_Secretary.mp3", "/audio/1772667612963-An_Administrative_La.mp3", "/audio/1772667613580-The_Florida_Real_Est.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1772667611821-The_Probable_Cause_P.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667612444-The_DBPR_Secretary.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667612963-An_Administrative_La.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667613580-The_Florida_Real_Est.timestamps.json"]	/audio/1772667611195-During_the_disciplin.mp3	/timestamps/1772667611195-During_the_disciplin.timestamps.json
cmms2nx7800i94be7adnvmcvc	cmmry1yz800fh4be796sih9l4	Listing agreements for the resale of a Time-Share must contain a disclosure stating:&nbsp;	{"The unit will sell within 90 days","The broker guarantees the sales price","There are no guarantees regarding price or when the unit may sell","The developer will buy back the unit if it doesn't sell"}	2	{"correct": "Florida law requires a specific disclosure that no guarantees exist regarding the sale price or timing, preventing misleading promises.", "incorrect": ["Brokers cannot guarantee sales or prices.", "Brokers cannot guarantee sales or prices.", "", "Developers are rarely under obligation to buy back resale units."]}	21	chapter	2026-03-15 18:12:29.78	2026-03-15 19:05:48.67	\N	\N	\N	\N	/audio/1773601545763-Florida_law_requires.mp3	/timestamps/1773601545763-Florida_law_requires.timestamps.json	["/audio/1773601546617-Brokers_cannot_guara.mp3", "/audio/1773601547572-Brokers_cannot_guara.mp3", "", "/audio/1773601548412-Developers_are_rarel.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1773601546617-Brokers_cannot_guara.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601547572-Brokers_cannot_guara.timestamps.json", "", "/timestamps/1773601548412-Developers_are_rarel.timestamps.json"]	["/audio/1773601540734-The_unit_will_sell_w.mp3", "/audio/1773601541856-The_broker_guarantee.mp3", "/audio/1773601542682-There_are_no_guarant.mp3", "/audio/1773601543706-The_developer_will_b.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1773601540734-The_unit_will_sell_w.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601541856-The_broker_guarantee.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601542682-There_are_no_guarant.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601543706-The_developer_will_b.timestamps.json"]	/audio/1773601539969-Listing_agreements_f.mp3	/timestamps/1773601539969-Listing_agreements_f.timestamps.json
cmmco0dpj003n3v02brdyfu0z	cmm58y7lt002j3t2wepydt1xl	Who decides if a probable cause exists?	{"Probable Cause Panel","FREC Attorney","FREC Secretary","DRE Panel"}	0	{"correct": "The Probable Cause Panel is responsible for determining whether probable cause exists to believe a licensee has violated real estate laws or rules. The panel acts much like a grand jury and is composed of two current or former FREC members (at least one of whom must be a current member).", "incorrect": ["", "The DBPR/FREC attorney prosecutes the case but does not make the formal decision on whether probable cause exists.", "FREC Secretary does not have the authority to declare probable cause.", "A general \\"DRE Panel\\" does not have the authority to declare probable cause."]}	22	chapter	2026-03-04 23:25:44.166	2026-03-04 23:40:30.14	\N	\N	\N	\N	/audio/1772667626618-The_Probable_Cause_P.mp3	/timestamps/1772667626618-The_Probable_Cause_P.timestamps.json	["", "/audio/1772667628028-The_DBPR_FREC_attorn.mp3", "/audio/1772667628905-FREC_Secretary_does_.mp3", "/audio/1772667629940-A_general__DRE_Panel.mp3"]	["", "/timestamps/1772667628028-The_DBPR_FREC_attorn.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667628905-FREC_Secretary_does_.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667629940-A_general__DRE_Panel.timestamps.json"]	["/audio/1772667622499-Probable_Cause_Panel.mp3", "/audio/1772667623124-FREC_Attorney.mp3", "/audio/1772667623778-FREC_Secretary.mp3", "/audio/1772667624358-DRE_Panel.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1772667622499-Probable_Cause_Panel.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667623124-FREC_Attorney.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667623778-FREC_Secretary.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667624358-DRE_Panel.timestamps.json"]	/audio/1772667621958-Who_decides_if_a_pro.mp3	/timestamps/1772667621958-Who_decides_if_a_pro.timestamps.json
cmmqxjecx00464be7a1en5h3n	cmmqbpz7v00044be7x0za79d7	Landlords of buildings with 5 or more units must give tenants the following disclosure:	{"Option to cancel lease within 5 days","Parking Space Assignment within 1 day","Structural Integrity Report for the building within 3 days","Where their deposit is being held within 30 days"}	3	{"correct": "Under Florida Statute 83.49, landlords who rent 5 or more individual dwelling units must provide written notice to the tenant within 30 days of receiving a security deposit or advance rent. This disclosure must state the name and address of the depository where the money is being held, and whether the tenant is entitled to interest on the deposit.", "incorrect": ["There is no statutory 5-day right of cancellation for standard residential leases in Florida.", "While a landlord might assign parking, there is no state law requiring a formal parking assignment disclosure within 1 day of leasing.", "Although structural integrity has become a major legislative focus in Florida (especially for condo associations), there is no blanket rule requiring landlords to hand a structural integrity report to new tenants within 3 days of signing a lease.", ""]}	31	chapter	2026-03-14 23:01:14.481	2026-03-14 23:16:21.911	\N	\N	\N	\N	/audio/1773530176206-Under_Florida_Statut.mp3	/timestamps/1773530176206-Under_Florida_Statut.timestamps.json	["/audio/1773530177639-There_is_no_statutor.mp3", "/audio/1773530179261-While_a_landlord_mig.mp3", "/audio/1773530181755-Although_structural_.mp3", ""]	["/timestamps/1773530177639-There_is_no_statutor.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530179261-While_a_landlord_mig.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530181755-Although_structural_.timestamps.json", ""]	["/audio/1773530170336-Option_to_cancel_lea.mp3", "/audio/1773530171185-Parking_Space_Assign.mp3", "/audio/1773530172054-Structural_Integrity.mp3", "/audio/1773530172985-Where_their_deposit_.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1773530170336-Option_to_cancel_lea.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530171185-Parking_Space_Assign.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530172054-Structural_Integrity.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530172985-Where_their_deposit_.timestamps.json"]	/audio/1773530169523-Landlords_of_buildin.mp3	/timestamps/1773530169523-Landlords_of_buildin.timestamps.json
cmmco2jgw003p3v02465puhyb	cmm58y7lt002j3t2wepydt1xl	A broker who was the listing agent, defrauded the seller but keeping their $30,000 deposit from a buyer. The seller took the broker to court and won the case. The court awarded a judgment in the amount of $40,000, plus additional $10,000 for punitive damages. The seller was not able to collect the judgment from the broker and requested Florida Real Estate Recovery Fund to pay out this amount. Which scenario is true?&nbsp;	{"Recovery Fund will not pay anything, because a lawsuit was involved","Recovery Fund may pay only $30,000","Recovery Fund may pay $40,000","Recovery Fund may pay only $10,000"}	2	{"correct": "The Florida Real Estate Recovery Fund reimburses consumers for compensatory (actual) damages up to a maximum of $50,000 per transaction. Since the court awarded $40,000 in actual compensatory damages, the fund will pay that full amount.", "incorrect": ["A civil lawsuit judgment against the broker is actually a requirement before a consumer can claim money from the Recovery Fund.", "While the original deposit was $30,000, the court determined the total actual/compensatory damages were $40,000. The fund pays the awarded compensatory judgment up to the $50k limit.", "", "The fund strictly prohibits the payout of punitive damages, treble damages, or interest. It will not pay the $10,000 punitive portion."]}	23	chapter	2026-03-04 23:27:24.944	2026-03-04 23:40:42.729	\N	\N	\N	\N	/audio/1772667638236-The_Florida_Real_Est.mp3	/timestamps/1772667638236-The_Florida_Real_Est.timestamps.json	["/audio/1772667639441-A_civil_lawsuit_judg.mp3", "/audio/1772667641160-While_the_original_d.mp3", "", "/audio/1772667642500-The_fund_strictly_pr.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1772667639441-A_civil_lawsuit_judg.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667641160-While_the_original_d.timestamps.json", "", "/timestamps/1772667642500-The_fund_strictly_pr.timestamps.json"]	["/audio/1772667633915-Recovery_Fund_will_n.mp3", "/audio/1772667634617-Recovery_Fund_may_pa.mp3", "/audio/1772667635339-Recovery_Fund_may_pa.mp3", "/audio/1772667636114-Recovery_Fund_may_pa.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1772667633915-Recovery_Fund_will_n.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667634617-Recovery_Fund_may_pa.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667635339-Recovery_Fund_may_pa.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667636114-Recovery_Fund_may_pa.timestamps.json"]	/audio/1772667633140-A_broker_who_was_the.mp3	/timestamps/1772667633140-A_broker_who_was_the.timestamps.json
cmmqxm5vh00484be7ww0jrbwi	cmmqbpz7v00044be7x0za79d7	The Fair Housing Act does NOT apply when:	{"50 unit rental building is being sold ","50 unit residential building owned by the government is being sold","Single family home being sold as for sale by owner, by an individual who owns 2 other single family homes","Single family home listed by a broker associate"}	2	{"correct": "The Fair Housing Act contains a specific exemption for the sale or rental of a single-family home by a private individual. This exemption is valid as long as the owner does not own more than three such homes at one time, the property is sold or rented without the use of a real estate broker (For Sale By Owner), and no discriminatory advertising is used. Because this private individual owns exactly three homes total (the one being sold plus two others) and is selling it FSBO without a licensee, the exemption legally applies.", "incorrect": ["The Fair Housing Act fully covers large multi-family apartment buildings. (The only multi-family exemption is for owner-occupied buildings with four or fewer units).", "Government-owned residential property is always bound by the Fair Housing Act with no exceptions.", "", "The moment a real estate licensee (broker or sales associate) is hired to help list, sell, or rent the property, the single-family exemption is instantly voided. Real estate professionals must always comply with the Fair Housing Act."]}	32	chapter	2026-03-14 23:03:23.453	2026-03-14 23:16:37.087	\N	\N	\N	\N	/audio/1773530191267-The_Fair_Housing_Act.mp3	/timestamps/1773530191267-The_Fair_Housing_Act.timestamps.json	["/audio/1773530193194-The_Fair_Housing_Act.mp3", "/audio/1773530194685-Government_owned_res.mp3", "", "/audio/1773530196920-The_moment_a_real_es.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1773530193194-The_Fair_Housing_Act.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530194685-Government_owned_res.timestamps.json", "", "/timestamps/1773530196920-The_moment_a_real_es.timestamps.json"]	["/audio/1773530183641-50_unit_rental_build.mp3", "/audio/1773530184578-50_unit_residential_.mp3", "/audio/1773530185789-Single_family_home_b.mp3", "/audio/1773530186700-Single_family_home_l.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1773530183641-50_unit_rental_build.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530184578-50_unit_residential_.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530185789-Single_family_home_b.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530186700-Single_family_home_l.timestamps.json"]	/audio/1773530182935-The_Fair_Housing_Act.mp3	/timestamps/1773530182935-The_Fair_Housing_Act.timestamps.json
cmmco61dj003r3v02pv8wwu4y	cmm58y7lt002j3t2wepydt1xl	A licensee received a citation from DRE which he/she doesn't agree with. Next step is to:&nbsp;	{"File a written objection within 30 days","File a written objection within 45 days","Request a hearing before the FREC within 30 days","Request a hearing before the FREC within 45 days"}	0	{"correct": "If a licensee receives a citation and believes it was issued in error, they have 30 days to file a written objection. If the citation is not disputed in writing within 30 days, it becomes a final order, and the penalty must be paid.", "incorrect": ["", "45 days is not a recognized timeframe for responding to DRE citations.", "While filing a written objection will trigger the formal disciplinary process (which may eventually lead to a hearing), the immediate required action is the written objection itself within 30 days.", "45 days is not a recognized timeframe for responding to DRE citations."]}	24	chapter	2026-03-04 23:30:08.119	2026-03-04 23:40:52.435	\N	\N	\N	\N	/audio/1772667648532-If_a_licensee_receiv.mp3	/timestamps/1772667648532-If_a_licensee_receiv.timestamps.json	["", "/audio/1772667649879-45_days_is_not_a_rec.mp3", "/audio/1772667651349-While_filing_a_writt.mp3", "/audio/1772667652283-45_days_is_not_a_rec.mp3"]	["", "/timestamps/1772667649879-45_days_is_not_a_rec.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667651349-While_filing_a_writt.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667652283-45_days_is_not_a_rec.timestamps.json"]	["/audio/1772667644472-File_a_written_objec.mp3", "/audio/1772667645196-File_a_written_objec.mp3", "/audio/1772667646049-Request_a_hearing_be.mp3", "/audio/1772667646780-Request_a_hearing_be.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1772667644472-File_a_written_objec.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667645196-File_a_written_objec.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667646049-Request_a_hearing_be.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667646780-Request_a_hearing_be.timestamps.json"]	/audio/1772667643849-A_licensee_received_.mp3	/timestamps/1772667643849-A_licensee_received_.timestamps.json
cmmco8mj5003t3v020ti0l44q	cmm58y7lt002j3t2wepydt1xl	How many days does a licensee have to notify DBPR of a conviction, plea, or adjudication of a crime, according to Florida Statute 455?	{"3 days","10 days","15 days","30 days"}	3	{"correct": "Under Florida Statute 455, a licensee must report to the DBPR within 30 days of being convicted of, found guilty of, or entering a plea of nolo contendere or guilty to a crime in any jurisdiction.", "incorrect": ["3 business days is the deadline for a broker to deposit escrow funds.", "10 days is the deadline to notify the DBPR of a change of mailing address or a change of employer.", "15 business days is the deadline for a broker to notify the FREC of conflicting demands on an escrow deposit.", ""]}	25	chapter	2026-03-04 23:32:08.849	2026-03-04 23:41:01.778	\N	\N	\N	\N	/audio/1772667658259-Under_Florida_Statut.mp3	/timestamps/1772667658259-Under_Florida_Statut.timestamps.json	["/audio/1772667659369-3_business_days_is_t.mp3", "/audio/1772667660458-10_days_is_the_deadl.mp3", "/audio/1772667661526-15_business_days_is_.mp3", ""]	["/timestamps/1772667659369-3_business_days_is_t.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667660458-10_days_is_the_deadl.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667661526-15_business_days_is_.timestamps.json", ""]	["/audio/1772667654546-3_days.mp3", "/audio/1772667655072-10_days.mp3", "/audio/1772667655685-15_days.mp3", "/audio/1772667656323-30_days.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1772667654546-3_days.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667655072-10_days.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667655685-15_days.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1772667656323-30_days.timestamps.json"]	/audio/1772667654040-How_many_days_does_a.mp3	/timestamps/1772667654040-How_many_days_does_a.timestamps.json
cmmqxnpwf004a4be72ccl68zu	cmmqbpz7v00044be7x0za79d7	A tenant has notified the landlord that they are going on a 7-day vacation. The landlord:	{"May enter tenant's rental premises with 2 witnesses","May not enter tenant's rental premises without tenant’s consent, except in an emergency","May not enter tenant's rental premises without a court order","May enter without restrictions"}	1	{"correct": "Under Florida Statute 83.53, if a tenant's rent is current and they officially notify the landlord of an intended absence (like a 7-day vacation), the landlord may only enter the dwelling unit with the tenant's explicit consent, or if it is strictly necessary for the \\"protection or preservation of the premises\\" (which translates to an active emergency, like a burst water pipe or a fire).", "incorrect": ["Florida law does not have any provisions requiring a landlord to bring witnesses in order to legally enter a rental property.", "", "&nbsp;A court order is not required for a landlord to enter a unit. They can enter with consent, proper statutory notice (usually 12 to 24 hours depending on the reason), or immediately during an emergency.", "A landlord never has completely unrestricted access to a rented property. The tenant has a legal right to privacy and quiet enjoyment, and the landlord must always abide by statutory notice and consent requirements, even when the tenant is out of town."]}	33	chapter	2026-03-14 23:04:36.063	2026-03-14 23:16:51.654	\N	\N	\N	\N	/audio/1773530205891-Under_Florida_Statut.mp3	/timestamps/1773530205891-Under_Florida_Statut.timestamps.json	["/audio/1773530207273-Florida_law_does_not.mp3", "", "/audio/1773530209272-A_court_order_is_not.mp3", "/audio/1773530211413-A_landlord_never_has.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1773530207273-Florida_law_does_not.timestamps.json", "", "/timestamps/1773530209272-A_court_order_is_not.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530211413-A_landlord_never_has.timestamps.json"]	["/audio/1773530199222-May_enter_tenant_s_r.mp3", "/audio/1773530200692-May_not_enter_tenant.mp3", "/audio/1773530201529-May_not_enter_tenant.mp3", "/audio/1773530202280-May_enter_without_re.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1773530199222-May_enter_tenant_s_r.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530200692-May_not_enter_tenant.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530201529-May_not_enter_tenant.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530202280-May_enter_without_re.timestamps.json"]	/audio/1773530198396-A_tenant_has_notifie.mp3	/timestamps/1773530198396-A_tenant_has_notifie.timestamps.json
cmmc62p3i00293v024alz0o7s	cmmbeuib8000m3v02t0xw15l9	How many questions are on the End-of-Course Exam?	{50,63,75,100}	3	{"correct": "The End-of-Course Exam consists of exactly 100 questions, intentionally mirroring the length of the actual state exam so there are no surprises.", "incorrect": ["The exam is longer than 50 questions to ensure comprehensive coverage of the material.", "The exam is longer than 63 questions to ensure comprehensive coverage of the material.", "75 is the required passing percentage, not the total number of questions on the exam.", ""]}	2	chapter	2026-03-04 15:03:39.15	2026-03-09 01:30:21.915	\N	\N	\N	\N	/audio/1773019684551-The_End_of_Course_Ex.mp3	/timestamps/1773019684551-The_End_of_Course_Ex.timestamps.json	["/audio/1773019685479-The_exam_is_longer_t.mp3", "/audio/1773019686520-The_exam_is_longer_t.mp3", "/audio/1773019687737-75_is_the_required_p.mp3", ""]	["/timestamps/1773019685479-The_exam_is_longer_t.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773019686520-The_exam_is_longer_t.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773019687737-75_is_the_required_p.timestamps.json", ""]	["/audio/1773019815523-50.mp3", "/audio/1773019816363-63.mp3", "/audio/1773019816916-75.mp3", "/audio/1773019817498-100.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1773019815523-50.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773019816363-63.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773019816916-75.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773019817498-100.timestamps.json"]	/audio/1773019814936-How_many_questions_a.mp3	/timestamps/1773019814936-How_many_questions_a.timestamps.json
cmmqxsgac004e4be7dhy9czrq	cmmqbpz7v00044be7x0za79d7	When drafting a property listing, a real estate licensee must strictly adhere to Fair Housing regulations. Which of the following marketing statements is legally permissible to publish?	{"\\"Charming starter property, ideal for someone looking to purchase their first house.\\"","\\"A wonderful area celebrated for its distinct racial demographics.\\"","\\"Exclusively catering to residents fluent in French.\\"","\\"Peaceful street, restricted to adults without toddlers.\\""}	0	{"correct": "The Fair Housing Act does not recognize \\"first-time homebuyers\\" as a protected class. Describing a home as a \\"starter property\\" refers to the property's likely price point and size, not a demographic preference, making it perfectly legal.", "incorrect": ["", "This is illegal because it violates the protected classes of race and national origin. Real estate advertising cannot express a preference for, or an exclusion of, specific ethnic backgrounds or language groups.", "This is illegal because it violates the protected classes of race and national origin. Real estate advertising cannot express a preference for, or an exclusion of, specific ethnic backgrounds or language groups.", "This statement illegally discriminates based on \\"familial status.\\" Unless the neighborhood is a legally registered \\"Housing for Older Persons\\" community (such as a 55+ development), you can never use advertising that discourages families with children from living there."]}	35	chapter	2026-03-14 23:08:16.884	2026-03-14 23:17:23.111	\N	\N	\N	\N	/audio/1773530236501-The_Fair_Housing_Act.mp3	/timestamps/1773530236501-The_Fair_Housing_Act.timestamps.json	["", "/audio/1773530238577-This_is_illegal_beca.mp3", "/audio/1773530240540-This_is_illegal_beca.mp3", "/audio/1773530242885-This_statement_illeg.mp3"]	["", "/timestamps/1773530238577-This_is_illegal_beca.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530240540-This_is_illegal_beca.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530242885-This_statement_illeg.timestamps.json"]	["/audio/1773530231219-_Charming_starter_pr.mp3", "/audio/1773530232188-_A_wonderful_area_ce.mp3", "/audio/1773530233176-_Exclusively_caterin.mp3", "/audio/1773530234146-_Peaceful_street__re.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1773530231219-_Charming_starter_pr.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530232188-_A_wonderful_area_ce.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530233176-_Exclusively_caterin.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773530234146-_Peaceful_street__re.timestamps.json"]	/audio/1773530230126-When_drafting_a_prop.mp3	/timestamps/1773530230126-When_drafting_a_prop.timestamps.json
cmms3r6r700in4be7vfyu2fmm	cmmry1yz800fh4be796sih9l4	Anna and Leon are a married couple who own a Florida homestead property together, with both of their names on the deed. They have three children. If Leon were to pass away, what would legally happen to the ownership of the homestead?	{"Anna receives a life estate, and the three children receive a vested remainder estate","Anna automatically owns the entire property in fee simple absolute through the right of survivorship","The property ownership is legally severed, with Anna retaining her 50% and the children inheriting Leon's 50%","The property must pass through probate before Anna can claim her dower rights"}	1	{"correct": "Because the homestead property was titled in both spouses' names, they own it as a Tenancy by the Entireties. This form of ownership includes the right of survivorship. When one spouse dies, the surviving spouse automatically absorbs the deceased spouse's share, leaving them with 100% ownership (fee simple absolute).", "incorrect": ["This is a very common trap on the state exam! The famous \\"life estate for the spouse / vested remainder for the children\\" rule only applies if the homestead property was owned in the sole name (severalty) of the deceased spouse. Because both Anna and Leon were on the deed, this rule does not trigger.", "", "A Tenancy by the Entireties cannot be willed away or divided upon death; it transfers wholly and automatically to the surviving spouse, bypassing the children entirely at this stage.", "The right of survivorship bypasses the probate process. Additionally, Florida abolished \\"dower and curtesy\\" rights decades ago, replacing them with the elective share and homestead protections."]}	28	chapter	2026-03-15 18:43:01.746	2026-03-15 19:07:35.685	\N	\N	\N	\N	/audio/1773601648996-Because_the_homestea.mp3	/timestamps/1773601648996-Because_the_homestea.timestamps.json	["/audio/1773601651683-This_is_a_very_commo.mp3", "", "/audio/1773601653570-A_Tenancy_by_the_Ent.mp3", "/audio/1773601655537-The_right_of_survivo.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1773601651683-This_is_a_very_commo.timestamps.json", "", "/timestamps/1773601653570-A_Tenancy_by_the_Ent.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601655537-The_right_of_survivo.timestamps.json"]	["/audio/1773601641964-Anna_receives_a_life.mp3", "/audio/1773601643311-Anna_automatically_o.mp3", "/audio/1773601644846-The_property_ownersh.mp3", "/audio/1773601645862-The_property_must_pa.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1773601641964-Anna_receives_a_life.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601643311-Anna_automatically_o.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601644846-The_property_ownersh.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601645862-The_property_must_pa.timestamps.json"]	/audio/1773601640903-Anna_and_Leon_are_a_.mp3	/timestamps/1773601640903-Anna_and_Leon_are_a_.timestamps.json
cmms40u5g00ix4be7ylwpzhf4	cmmry1yz800fh4be796sih9l4	In Florida, the creation, governance, and management of cooperative associations are strictly regulated by which state agency?	{"The Florida Real Estate Commission (FREC)","The Division of Real Estate (DRE)","The Department of Housing and Urban Development (HUD)","The Division of Florida Condominiums, Timeshares, and Mobile Homes"}	3	{"correct": "Under Florida law, the Division of Florida Condominiums, Timeshares, and Mobile Homes (which operates under the umbrella of the Department of Business and Professional Regulation, or DBPR) is the specific regulatory agency responsible for overseeing cooperatives, as well as condos, timeshares, and mobile home parks. They handle arbitration, complaints, and ensure associations comply with state statutes.", "incorrect": ["The Florida Real Estate Commission (FREC) regulates real estate licensees (brokers, sales associates, and schools), but it does not have jurisdiction over the legal operation or governance of the cooperative associations themselves.", "The Division of Real Estate (DRE) provides administrative support and handles licensing paperwork for FREC, but it does not regulate cooperatives.", "HUD is a federal agency. While HUD enforces federal laws like the Fair Housing Act, the specific formation and daily regulation of Florida cooperatives is handled at the state level by the Division.", ""]}	33	chapter	2026-03-15 18:50:31.972	2026-03-15 19:08:56.242	\N	\N	\N	\N	/audio/1773601730327-Under_Florida_law__t.mp3	/timestamps/1773601730327-Under_Florida_law__t.timestamps.json	["/audio/1773601732871-The_Florida_Real_Est.mp3", "/audio/1773601734215-The_Division_of_Real.mp3", "/audio/1773601736094-HUD_is_a_federal_age.mp3", ""]	["/timestamps/1773601732871-The_Florida_Real_Est.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601734215-The_Division_of_Real.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601736094-HUD_is_a_federal_age.timestamps.json", ""]	["/audio/1773601723189-The_Florida_Real_Est.mp3", "/audio/1773601724531-The_Division_of_Real.mp3", "/audio/1773601725602-The_Department_of_Ho.mp3", "/audio/1773601726471-The_Division_of_Flor.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1773601723189-The_Florida_Real_Est.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601724531-The_Division_of_Real.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601725602-The_Department_of_Ho.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601726471-The_Division_of_Flor.timestamps.json"]	/audio/1773601722308-In_Florida__the_crea.mp3	/timestamps/1773601722308-In_Florida__the_crea.timestamps.json
cmms42ded00iz4be7oqgitagi	cmmry1yz800fh4be796sih9l4	Under Florida law, what is the legally required rescission (cancellation) period for a buyer who is purchasing a new condominium unit from a developer?	{"3 days ","10 days ","15 days ","20 days "}	2	{"correct": "A buyer purchasing a new condominium directly from a developer has a 15-day right to cancel the contract after signing and receiving all required developer documents.&nbsp;", "incorrect": ["3 days is not enough time.&nbsp;", "10 days is not enough time.&nbsp;", "", "20 days is incorrect.&nbsp;"]}	34	chapter	2026-03-15 18:51:43.573	2026-03-15 19:09:04.352	\N	\N	\N	\N	/audio/1773601742008-A_buyer_purchasing_a.mp3	/timestamps/1773601742008-A_buyer_purchasing_a.timestamps.json	["/audio/1773601742986-3_days_is_not_enough.mp3", "/audio/1773601743591-10_days_is_not_enoug.mp3", "", "/audio/1773601744205-20_days_is_incorrect.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1773601742986-3_days_is_not_enough.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601743591-10_days_is_not_enoug.timestamps.json", "", "/timestamps/1773601744205-20_days_is_incorrect.timestamps.json"]	["/audio/1773601738404-3_days.mp3", "/audio/1773601738928-10_days.mp3", "/audio/1773601739488-15_days.mp3", "/audio/1773601740030-20_days.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1773601738404-3_days.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601738928-10_days.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601739488-15_days.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601740030-20_days.timestamps.json"]	/audio/1773601737869-Under_Florida_law__w.mp3	/timestamps/1773601737869-Under_Florida_law__w.timestamps.json
cmms0af7k00h34be7jifnv93i	cmmry1yz800fh4be796sih9l4	Which term is defined as the surface of the earth and everything attached to it by nature, such as trees and water?	{"Real Estate",Land,"Real Property","Leasehold Estate"}	1	{"correct": "Land refers strictly to the earth's surface and natural attachments (trees, water, boulders).", "incorrect": ["Real Estate includes land plus man-made improvements (houses, fences).", "", "Real Property includes real estate plus the legal bundle of rights.", "A Leasehold Estate is a tenant's interest in a property, not the physical land itself."]}	0	chapter	2026-03-15 17:06:00.704	2026-03-15 19:02:37.565	\N	\N	\N	\N	/audio/1773601354264-Land_refers_strictly.mp3	/timestamps/1773601354264-Land_refers_strictly.timestamps.json	["/audio/1773601355552-Real_Estate_includes.mp3", "", "/audio/1773601356535-Real_Property_includ.mp3", "/audio/1773601357414-A_Leasehold_Estate_i.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1773601355552-Real_Estate_includes.timestamps.json", "", "/timestamps/1773601356535-Real_Property_includ.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601357414-A_Leasehold_Estate_i.timestamps.json"]	["/audio/1773601351208-Real_Estate.mp3", "/audio/1773601351747-Land.mp3", "/audio/1773601352327-Real_Property.mp3", "/audio/1773601352962-Leasehold_Estate.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1773601351208-Real_Estate.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601351747-Land.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601352327-Real_Property.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601352962-Leasehold_Estate.timestamps.json"]	/audio/1773601350661-Which_term_is_define.mp3	/timestamps/1773601350661-Which_term_is_define.timestamps.json
cmms0d13l00h54be7egd52psi	cmmry1yz800fh4be796sih9l4	What is the definition of Real Estate?	{"Land plus the bundle of rights","Land and all human-made improvements","Tangible assets that are movable"," The surface of the earth and natural attachments only"}	1	{"correct": "Real Estate is defined as the land plus permanent human-made additions (improvements) like buildings and sewers.", "incorrect": ["This defines Real Property.", "", "This defines Personal Property.", "This defines Land."]}	1	chapter	2026-03-15 17:08:02.385	2026-03-15 19:02:45.674	\N	\N	\N	\N	/audio/1773601363461-Real_Estate_is_defin.mp3	/timestamps/1773601363461-Real_Estate_is_defin.timestamps.json	["/audio/1773601364162-This_defines_Real_Pr.mp3", "", "/audio/1773601364840-This_defines_Persona.mp3", "/audio/1773601365444-This_defines_Land_.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1773601364162-This_defines_Real_Pr.timestamps.json", "", "/timestamps/1773601364840-This_defines_Persona.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601365444-This_defines_Land_.timestamps.json"]	["/audio/1773601359071-Land_plus_the_bundle.mp3", "/audio/1773601360141-Land_and_all_human_m.mp3", "/audio/1773601360871-Tangible_assets_that.mp3", "/audio/1773601361828-The_surface_of_the_e.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1773601359071-Land_plus_the_bundle.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601360141-Land_and_all_human_m.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601360871-Tangible_assets_that.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601361828-The_surface_of_the_e.timestamps.json"]	/audio/1773601358346-What_is_the_definiti.mp3	/timestamps/1773601358346-What_is_the_definiti.timestamps.json
cmms0gb2500h74be74hnp5omt	cmmry1yz800fh4be796sih9l4	Real Property is best described as:	{"The land and improvements minus the mineral rights","All real estate plus the legal bundle of rights","Only the man-made improvements on the land","Personal property that has become a fixture"}	1	{"correct": "Real Property encompasses the physical real estate (land + improvements) and the intangible legal rights associated with ownership (the bundle of rights).", "incorrect": ["Mineral rights are part of the real property unless specifically excluded; \\"minus\\" makes this incorrect.", "", "This is only a component of real estate, not the full definition of real property.", "This describes a fixture, which is a specific type of real property, but not the definition of the concept."]}	2	chapter	2026-03-15 17:10:35.261	2026-03-15 19:02:55.946	\N	\N	\N	\N	/audio/1773601371979-Real_Property_encomp.mp3	/timestamps/1773601371979-Real_Property_encomp.timestamps.json	["/audio/1773601373338-Mineral_rights_are_p.mp3", "", "/audio/1773601374442-This_is_only_a_compo.mp3", "/audio/1773601375800-This_describes_a_fix.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1773601373338-Mineral_rights_are_p.timestamps.json", "", "/timestamps/1773601374442-This_is_only_a_compo.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601375800-This_describes_a_fix.timestamps.json"]	["/audio/1773601367617-The_land_and_improve.mp3", "/audio/1773601368468-All_real_estate_plus.mp3", "/audio/1773601369331-Only_the_man_made_im.mp3", "/audio/1773601370183-Personal_property_th.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1773601367617-The_land_and_improve.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601368468-All_real_estate_plus.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601369331-Only_the_man_made_im.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601370183-Personal_property_th.timestamps.json"]	/audio/1773601366654-Real_Property_is_bes.mp3	/timestamps/1773601366654-Real_Property_is_bes.timestamps.json
cmms0i0jm00h94be7l8j13l6o	cmmry1yz800fh4be796sih9l4	The physical components of land include which three rights?	{"Surface, Subsurface, and Air rights","Possession, Control, and Exclusion rights","Riparian, Littoral, and Erosion rights","Disposition, Enjoyment, and Surface rights"}	0	{"correct": "Land ownership is 3-dimensional, consisting of Surface rights (ground), Subsurface rights (minerals/oil), and Air rights (space above).", "incorrect": ["", "These are legal rights (Bundle of Rights), not physical components.", "These are water-related concepts, not the three primary physical components.", "This mixes legal rights with one physical component."]}	3	chapter	2026-03-15 17:11:54.946	2026-03-15 19:03:05.813	\N	\N	\N	\N	/audio/1773601382359-Land_ownership_is_3_.mp3	/timestamps/1773601382359-Land_ownership_is_3_.timestamps.json	["", "/audio/1773601383562-These_are_legal_righ.mp3", "/audio/1773601384751-These_are_water_rela.mp3", "/audio/1773601385662-This_mixes_legal_rig.mp3"]	["", "/timestamps/1773601383562-These_are_legal_righ.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601384751-These_are_water_rela.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601385662-This_mixes_legal_rig.timestamps.json"]	["/audio/1773601377798-Surface__Subsurface_.mp3", "/audio/1773601378553-Possession__Control_.mp3", "/audio/1773601379506-Riparian__Littoral__.mp3", "/audio/1773601380341-Disposition__Enjoyme.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1773601377798-Surface__Subsurface_.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601378553-Possession__Control_.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601379506-Riparian__Littoral__.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601380341-Disposition__Enjoyme.timestamps.json"]	/audio/1773601376897-The_physical_compone.mp3	/timestamps/1773601376897-The_physical_compone.timestamps.json
cmms0n1jw00hd4be7y8pkljhk	cmmry1yz800fh4be796sih9l4	Which of the following is NOT one of the four legal tests for determining if an item is a fixture?	{" Intent of the parties","Cost of the item","Method or degree of attachment","Adaptation of the item"}	1	{"correct": "The Cost of the item is not a legal test for fixtures. An expensive item can be personal property, and a cheap item can be a fixture.", "incorrect": ["Intent is the most important test (did they mean for it to stay?).", "", "Method of attachment (is it screwed in?) is a valid test.", "Adaptation (was it custom-made for the house?) is a valid test. The fourth test is the Relationship/Agreement of the parties."]}	5	chapter	2026-03-15 17:15:49.531	2026-03-15 19:03:24.279	\N	\N	\N	\N	/audio/1773601400564-The_Cost_of_the_item.mp3	/timestamps/1773601400564-The_Cost_of_the_item.timestamps.json	["/audio/1773601401660-Intent_is_the_most_i.mp3", "", "/audio/1773601402615-Method_of_attachment.mp3", "/audio/1773601404110-Adaptation__was_it_c.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1773601401660-Intent_is_the_most_i.timestamps.json", "", "/timestamps/1773601402615-Method_of_attachment.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601404110-Adaptation__was_it_c.timestamps.json"]	["/audio/1773601397124-Intent_of_the_partie.mp3", "/audio/1773601397654-Cost_of_the_item.mp3", "/audio/1773601398330-Method_or_degree_of_.mp3", "/audio/1773601398988-Adaptation_of_the_it.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1773601397124-Intent_of_the_partie.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601397654-Cost_of_the_item.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601398330-Method_or_degree_of_.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601398988-Adaptation_of_the_it.timestamps.json"]	/audio/1773601396327-Which_of_the_followi.mp3	/timestamps/1773601396327-Which_of_the_followi.timestamps.json
cmms0k36p00hb4be780cczjzd	cmmry1yz800fh4be796sih9l4	Any tangible asset that is NOT real property is generally classified as:	{"A Fixture","Personal Property","A Trade Fixture","An Improvement"}	1	{"correct": "Personal Property (or chattel) consists of items that are temporary, movable, and not permanently attached to the land.", "incorrect": ["A fixture was personal property but has become real property.", "", "A trade fixture is a specific type of commercial personal property, but \\"Personal Property\\" is the broader, correct classification for the definition.", "An improvement is a man-made attachment that is considered real estate."]}	4	chapter	2026-03-15 17:13:31.681	2026-03-15 19:03:14.856	\N	\N	\N	\N	/audio/1773601390983-Personal_Property__o.mp3	/timestamps/1773601390983-Personal_Property__o.timestamps.json	["/audio/1773601392234-A_fixture_was_person.mp3", "", "/audio/1773601393764-A_trade_fixture_is_a.mp3", "/audio/1773601394658-An_improvement_is_a_.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1773601392234-A_fixture_was_person.timestamps.json", "", "/timestamps/1773601393764-A_trade_fixture_is_a.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601394658-An_improvement_is_a_.timestamps.json"]	["/audio/1773601387624-A_Fixture.mp3", "/audio/1773601388166-Personal_Property.mp3", "/audio/1773601389038-A_Trade_Fixture.mp3", "/audio/1773601389540-An_Improvement.mp3"]	["/timestamps/1773601387624-A_Fixture.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601388166-Personal_Property.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601389038-A_Trade_Fixture.timestamps.json", "/timestamps/1773601389540-An_Improvement.timestamps.json"]	/audio/1773601387074-Any_tangible_asset_t.mp3	/timestamps/1773601387074-Any_tangible_asset_t.timestamps.json
